<subSubSection lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="371" pageId="12" pageNumber="370" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1734,2013]" lastBlockId="13.[151,1437,151,1761]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="371" pageId="12" pageNumber="370">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1878,1904]" pageId="12" pageNumber="370">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new species differs from other species of the genus in the forewing with a purplish black streak in the distal half along midline; in the male genitalia by the sub-quadrate juxta shallowly concave in U-shape posteromedially; in the female genitalia by the C-shaped signum, and the ductus seminalis inflated elliptically at middle. It is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick, 1913" authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1913" box="[401,705,1986,2013]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Stathmopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stimulata">
<emphasis box="[401,532,1986,2013]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="370">S. stimulata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Meyrick, E." box="[538,705,1986,2012]" pageId="12" pageNumber="370" pagination="136 - 141" refId="ref15844" refString="Meyrick, E. (1913) Exotic Microlepidoptera, 1 (3), 65 - 96. Marborough. Nagano, K. (1916) On a new micropterous moth from Japan. Konch Sek, 20 (4), 136 - 141." type="journal article" year="1913">Meyrick, 1913</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished in the male genitalia by the straight apex of the uncus, the ovate cucullus convex before middle on the dorsal margin and the cornutus of the aedeagus with six spines; and in the female genitalia by the corpus bursae with one signum. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1913" box="[1042,1174,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Stathmopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="371" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stimulata">
<emphasis box="[1042,1174,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="371">S. stimulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the uncus is pointed at apex, the cucullus is strongly produced at base dorsally and the cornutus of the aedeagus consists of 3–5 spines in the male genitalia; and the corpus bursae has two signa in the female genitalia (
<bibRefCitation author="Kasy, F." box="[1048,1173,259,285]" pageId="13" pageNumber="371" pagination="227 - 299" refId="ref15655" refString="Kasy, F. (1973) Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Familie Stathmopodidae Meyrick, 1913 (Lepidoptera, Gelechioidea). Tijdschriftvoor Entomologie, 116 (13), 227 - 299." type="journal article" year="1973">Kasy 1973</bibRefCitation>
, P. 286, Figs 84, 86). It is also similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Wang &amp; Guan &amp; Wang, 2020" authorityName="Wang &amp; Guan &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2020" box="[346,527,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Stathmopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="371" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falsistimulata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[346,527,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="371">S. falsistimulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[535,625,295,321]" pageId="13" pageNumber="371">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[535,625,295,321]" pageId="13" pageNumber="371" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, and the differences between the two species are stated in the diagnosis of the latter species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
